<HEADLINE>
STARTING SALARIES FOR NEW TERTIARY GRADUATES UP: POLL
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 24 (CNA) 05/24/07  20:44:39 (By Flor Wang)
</P>
<P>
Starting salaries offered by local private companies to 2007
tertiary education graduates are up between 2.5 percent and 5
percent, according to the results of a survey released Thursday
by a human resources company.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll conducted by 104 human resources bank, this
year's master degree holders are being offered starting salaries
averaging NT$32,755 (nearly US$1,000), up by 4.95 percent
compared to the 2004 level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the averages for new university and college graduates
stand at NT$28,631 and NT$26,030, up by 3.51 percent and 2.57
percent, respectively, the survey indicated.
</P>
<P>
However, only this year's post-graduates will enjoy a substantial
pay raise of 1.38 percentage points after adjustments for
consumer price inflation, which has risen 3.57 percent per year
on average in the last three years, the poll found.
</P>
<P>
In term of industries, new tertiary graduates in the information
technology- related sector can command a starting salary of
NT$30,357, while those in the manufacturing and medical
treatment/environmental hygiene  sectors  are being offered
NT$28,228  and NT$27,927, respectively.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, some 67 percent of businesses responding to the
survey -- mostly in the insurance and financial management,
services and house construction  and real-estate  sectors  --
expressed willingness to hire new workers this year, according to
the survey.
</P>
<P>
The 104 executive research bank carried out the poll from May
9-14, collecting 844 valid questionnaires. It had a margin of
error of 3.3 percentage points.
</P>
